Busy old fool, unruly Sun,
Why dost thou thus,
Through windows, and through curtains call on us?
Must to thy motions lovers' seasons run?
Saucy pedantic wretch, go chide
Late school boys, and sour prentices,
Go tell court huntsmen that the king will ride,
Call country ants to harvest offices;
Love, all alike, no season knows, nor clime,
Nor hours, days, months, which are the rags of time.
Thy beams, so reverend and strong
Why shouldst thou think?
I could eclipse and cloud them with a wink,
But that I would not lose her sight so long:
If her eyes have not blinded thine,
Look, and tomorrow late, tell me,
Whether both the Indias of spice and mine
Be where thou leftst them, or lie here with me.
Ask for those kings whom thou saw'st yesterday,
And thou shalt hear, All here in one bed lay.
She's all states, and all princes, I,
Nothing else is.
Princes do but play us; compared to this,
All honor's mimic, all wealth alchemy.
Thou, sun, art half as happy as we,
In that the world's contracted thus;
Thine age asks ease, and since thy duties be
To warm the world, that's done in warming us.
Shine here to us, and thou art everywhere;
This bed thy center is, these walls, thy sphere.

Like stars in heaven, and joyously they sail;

As if with silken wings they took their flight.

The sun did shine upon the waters wide,
And in its light the waves did dance and play;
The ships did seem to float upon the tide,
As if they were the children of the day.

The sea was blue, the sky was clear and fair,
The ships did seem to laugh and sing with glee;
And as they sailed along the ocean's air,
They seemed to say, 'We're happy as can be.'

But lo! a storm arose upon the sea,
And darkened all the sky with clouds of grey;
The ships were tossed about tumultuously,
And many a one was wrecked upon the spray.

The sun did hide its face, the winds did roar,
The waves did rage and foam upon the deep;
The ships did seem to struggle evermore,
And some did founder, and their crews to weep.

But some did brave the storm, and reach the shore,
And safe from harm, their cargoes to unload;
And as they anchored there, they did deplore
The fate of those that in the tempest road.

And thus it is with life, both high and low,
Some sail in calm, and some in stormy weather;
But those that brave the storm, they often show
A strength of heart that's more than gold or leather.
